SIMPLE: stool
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stool
<hw>Stool</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>stolo</ets>.
See <er>Stolon</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Hort.)</fld> <def>A plant from which
layers are propagated by bending its branches into the soil.</def>
<rj><au>P. Henderson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stool</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stool
<hw>Stool</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Agric.)</fld> <def>To ramify; to
tiller, as grain; to shoot out suckers.</def> <rj><au>R. D.
Blackmore.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stool</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stool
<hw>Stool</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>st⟦omac⟧l</ets> a seat; akin to OFries. & OS. <ets>st⟦omac⟧l</ets>,
D. <ets>stoel</ets>, G. <ets>stuhl</ets>, OHG. <ets>stuol</ets>, Icel.
<ets>st⟦omac⟧ll</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>stol</ets>, Goth.
<ets>st⟦omac⟧ls</ets>, Lith. <ets>stalas</ets> a table, Russ.
<ets>stol'</ets>; from the root of E. <ets>stand</ets>. ⟦root⟧163. See
<er>Stand</er>, and cf. <er>Fauteuil</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
single seat with three or four legs and without a back, made in various
forms for various uses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A seat used in evacuating the bowels; hence, an
evacuation; a discharge from the bowels.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A stool pigeon, or decoy bird.</def> <mark>[U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A small channel on the side of a
vessel, for the dead-eyes of the backstays.</def>
<rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A bishop's seat or see; a bishop-stool.</def>
<rj><au>J. P. Peters.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A bench or form for resting the feet or the knees; a
footstool; <as>as, a kneeling <ex>stool</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Material, such as oyster shells, spread on the sea
bottom for oyster spat to adhere to.</def> <mark>[Local,
U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Stool of a window</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Window stool</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>the flat
piece upon which the window shuts down, and which corresponds to the
sill of a door; in the United States, the narrow shelf fitted on the
inside against the actual sill upon which the sash descends. This is
called a <xex>window seat</xex> when broad and low enough to be used as
a seat.</cd> -- <col><b>Stool of repentance</b></col>, <cd>the
cuttystool.</cd> <mark>[Scot.]</mark> -- <col><b>Stool pigeon</b></col>,
<cd>a pigeon used as a decoy to draw others within a net; hence, a
person used as a decoy for others.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stoolball</ent>⟦br⟧
